{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Integrative Close: Circuit Loading Analysis",
    "objective": "Apply unit conversion, formula transposition, and percentage factors to evaluate circuit suitability.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "To verify if an installation is safe and compliant, you must often combine several mathematical steps. This involves converting power ratings using indices (powers of ten), transposing formulas to find the operating current, and applying percentage-based limits to protective devices.",
      "In this scenario, you are checking if a circuit breaker can handle a specific load under restricted conditions. You must first find the actual current (I) and then compare it to the adjusted (derated) limit of the breaker."
    ],
    "questionText": "A 5.75 kW electric heater is installed on a 230 V circuit protected by a 32 A circuit breaker. Due to high ambient temperatures, the breaker's effective capacity must be derated to 80% of its nominal value. Calculate the heater's operating current and state whether the breaker's derated capacity is sufficient to carry this load.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "5750 W",
      "25 A",
      "25.6 A",
      "The current is 25 A (5750 / 230).",
      "The derated limit is 25.6 A (32 x 0.8).",
      "Yes, it is sufficient because 25 A is less than 25.6 A."
    ],
    "hint": "First, convert 5.75 kW to Watts (10³). Then, transpose P = V x I to find the current. Finally, calculate 80% of 32 A (32 x 0.8) and compare the two values."
  }
}

